<br>
The &quot;Efficiency Path,&quot; as I have described, affects all playstyles, and allows a great deal of flexibility when things don't go according to plan.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Get as many FT items and as big a mana pool as your playstyle will allow you, and go for those AA skills that help in this area<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
... or use pet canni during your downtime.  Pure evocation is intrinsically less efficient and needs to be heavily subsidized by Flowing Thought and outside Clarity buffs.  Heavy outside buffing of the pets helps as well.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>SCF is a total no brainer as first choice, or was for me,<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Really?  I would have thought that even for Evocationists, the efficiency of SCM would have been the no-brainer as first choice.  Like I said already, SCM maxed gives a 15% boost to efficiency for ALL spells.  SCF maxed gives 7%, and ONLY for nukes/rains.  Apparently a bigger bang is more important to an Evocationist than being able to sustain smaller bangs.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>As for the class skills, I even looked at QS, but frankly for the evocation mage, reduced time on CoH is not a good reason to spend so many points.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
QS 3= FT 95+ when using pet canni (deducting the mana regen bonus of meditate).  Without the summoning hastes, that drops to about FT 35+.  I can see why someone would not choose the mana regen benefits of Quick Summoning, being Evoc specialized and all...<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Get as many <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>FT items</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->... and go for those AA skills that help in this area.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Looks to me you just contradicted yourself.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>And I think I will be buying 15 points in resists before I waste aaxp on IR or EP, things that are of zero use to me.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
This is what IR means:  No matter how injured your pet is, or how low in mana you are, you will always have at least enough mana for one more pet.  That would benefit every single magician in the game, except you of course.<br>
<br>
This is what EP means:  No matter how little malachite you have, you will still be able to reclaim pets for mana, or get one more pet up for battle.  That would also benefit every single magician in the game, except you, like you stated.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Well, it is another path.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
That it is.  Perhaps not optimal, but definitely another path.  &quot;Optimal&quot; involves getting the most effect for the least effort and fewest AA's spent.  One way to optimize on the Quick Summoning path is to only get QS 2 and a Summoning Haste item.  That would save 9 AA points.<br>
<br>
As a side note, there is nothing wrong with getting the bigger bangs of Fury, but efficiency should be the primary focus, and in the order of greatest effect first.  I fully intend to increase my efficiency by buying Fury and Clarity, but they were not the highest priority early on.  With the advent of reclaim chaining, I can take my time getting those skills, since I am never lacking for mana anyway.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Get as many FT items and as big a mana pool as your playstyle will allow you<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
LOL  I have FT 0, a mana pool of approximately 2800 or so, and like I just said, I am never lacking for mana.  I can sit if I want, or stand, nuke when I want (or need), refuse to buy or beg for clarity buffs, and still not worry about my mana needs.  This sounds quite optimal to me. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=jochangaladar>Jochan Galadar</A> at: 2/12/03 8:44:35 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=cydmab>Cydmab</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Sage</span><br>  Posts: 787<br> <font color=#333333>(2/12/03 9:35:30 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=540.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Optimal AA path for magicians</span><hr size=1> Quote:<br>
<br>
Pet discipline in a raid environmet I don't entirely understand. If I am engaged with our target, my pet is up and fighting. If not, I am using pet canni, CoH, summoning focus gear, or mass rodding. If nothing is being engaged, there is no need to have a pet up, but with QS 3, a new pet is only a few short seconds away. If aoe cross-aggro is an issue, then you are probably better off canni/nuking. If enrage is an issue, then either reposition your pet or reclaim it and resummon just before enrage ends (Quick Summoning helps immensely.)<br>
<br>
Enquote<br>
<br>
I guess this is how I see it. I have so much mana regen under raid conditions, that I very, very rarely need to cannapet. I'm aggro constrained. Even if I were low on mana, pet does a tremendous amount of aggro-free damage. Depending on your gear and spells, pet cannabilizing for extra nukes when you could be just sending in your high dps water pet can be a wash or even harmful. (Pet can do over 100 dps, including procs. If you get 5DPMana, then you must generate about 120 mana/tic from pet cannabilizing , including refresh times between spells, messups, pet suspends, (if you save an armed and buffed pet), and the time it takes to dump that mana into nukes. <br>
<br>
I have a higher standard of pet being fully controlled then just if there are aoe's about: I want the pet to be under full control when any adds are incoming, so enchanters can handle cc without any risk from me. To do this one can:<br>
 <br>
1. Use pet hold until things calm down<br>
2. Destroy the pet<br>
3. Use back off liberally and focus very carefully on what the pet is doing.<br>
4. suspend the pet<br>
<br>
Option 1 solves the problem nicely. Using option 2 regularly means it's difficult to keep the pet shrunk, and almost impossible to keep the pet armed with procing weapons (there goes 10dps of aggro-free damage). It also wastes 5+2.25 seconds to remake the pet, plus time to burnout the pet. If the time of pet control danger is short (say, a multi-pull and waiting 5 seconds for the enchanters to mez extra mobs) then this can be very costly. Option 3 means stress, lots amount of trust from my guild, and alot of focus, which can prevent me from nuking, cohing pullers/late comers, summoning rods, malosinia duty, or other functions. Option 4 is slow like option 2 and costs even more AA than pet hold. It also fails if the pet does accidently aggro something before you get the effect to work.<br>
<br>
That said, I must admit I sometimes take FT15 and the option to pet cannabilize for granted. There's a good case for the following initial AA lineup, especially if you solo/duo alot:<br>
<br>
run 3<br>
regen 3<br>
SCM 3<br>
QS 2<br>
Suspend companion 2<br>
<br>
I'm hostile to IR (kinda screwy effects with rathe's son, some good, some very bad), EP (don't need if you have rathe's son and I never found having a backpack of malachite a horrid burden), and QS3 (10% bonus for 9AA, and doesn't apply if you have a summoning haste focus or blessing of reverence). OTOH some of these objections revolve around the 65 pet. If you know you won't have Rathe's son ever, then they would not apply. <p>Master Cydmab Promethean<br>
Arch Convoker of Morell Thule<br>
Fury's Edge</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=goladus>Goladus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Grand Poobah Goladus</span><br>  Posts: 2655<br> <font color=#333333>(2/12/03 11:09:42 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=540.topic&index=23>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://doug.feldmann.com/Sigurd.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Optimal AA path for magicians</span><hr size=1> About pet hold:<br>
<br>
Like Cydmab said, after aggro and other considerations mana is generally not really high on the list of limiting factors that go into most boss fights.  I hit pet hold on raids all the time, if I had to reclaim my pet every single time that happens I would go nuts.<br>
<br>
At the very least, /pet hold lets me summon, pre-buff, and pre-equip a pet no matter what the situation will be <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">even an unknown situation</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->.  Using reclaim/resummon to pull my pet off every single time it needed to be moved would not only make me go insane, but would lower my pet's damage output, and quite possibly my nuke output as well.  I can even /pet hold mid-nuke if I want to.<br>
<br>
Yes, for some fights mana is an issue, although for a single encounter it's rare that you would actually want to take your pet off the target in order to reclaim nuke mana.  Chaining pets is also useful in certian fights, particularly if there is a nasty AE.  I'm not saying IRE, QS, and EP are useless on raids and /pet hold is godly, but to break it down by skill:<br>
<br>
IRE:  3 points for an ability with questionable use.. if you really like cannibalize it's already possible with the 49 pets.  That should hold you over for the 6 points needed to get pet hold.  Maybe reclaiming low health pets against AE dragons would be more useful than I'm giving it credit for, I just seem to remember my pets lasting fairly well through most fights, even with AEs.  But at 3 points I don't really think this one is a big deal either way.<br>
<br>
QS3:  This costs 18 points and all it really does relative to hold is make the raid workarounds go a little more quickly.  There are still hard drawbacks.  At the very least 6 points into pet hold is more useful than the 9 to upgrade QS2 to QS3.  I can see an argument for QS2 before /pet hold, especially since it works on CoTH, but I would still say /pet hold is generally more practical.<br>
<br>
Elemental Pact:  This is really only for convenience.  While there are tangible drawbacks that you will almost certianly encounter trying to reclaim/resummon pets instead of using /pet hold, you can simulate 99% of elemental pact by bringing a backpack full of malachite to the raid.  Sure, go ahead and get Elemental Pact, it most certianly convenient, but definitely not more than /pet hold.  I would almost suggest /pet hold over EP for a non-raiding mage.<br>
