<br>
I know you love Pet Canni / Chaining as *your* style. You post it all over these forums, and you are entitled to do so, as can anyone. You are free to follow the style you like. You can even make claims of greater 'efficiency' or being more 'optimal' for your own approach, something many of us will not agree with but there you go.<br>
<br>
I put one line near the top of my first post saying I am no fan of Pet Canni [PC] (and implicitly of Chaining Pets [CP]), and went on to make my own recommendations based on an evocationalist wizzie+pet sustainer playstyle.<br>
<br>
You replied by ever so helpfully explaining how the AA skills worked, as if clearly those who do not follow your gospel do not understand, and then used the facts of how they work to somehow draw the conclusion that your style is more efficient. Sorry sir, we do understand, we just do not all agree with your conclusions; it is almost as if your post is designed by it <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>tone</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to start a 'fight' lol.<br>
<br>
I have a number of problems with PC/CP:<br>
<br>
1) I am a roleplayer, and PC makes no roleplay sense. I summon a being from another plane, to assist me. It is bound to my soul for it's duration by my side, and we become allies. It is not a captive enemy, it cons amiable. I do not senselessly and repeatedly murder it for ... mana gain. How anti-thematic can one be? /shrug, this is a personal thing.<br>
<br>
2) Roleplay aside, it still makes no sense, it feels like an exploit, or at least, a cheesy gimp tactic for those unskilled to do things 'properly'. Summoning and killing a pet to gain mana just seems wrong. Really, I don't feel it *should* work, and I'd be one mage who wouldn't miss it if it were removed totally [and yes, I know it does work for regening mana grandmother, eggs, etcetera, but there are other factors you are quietly ignoring].<br>
<br>
Now, ok, these are not going to worry most people, and I'd possibly push them aside if it was not for:<br>
<br>
3) It isn't fun, it is merely irritating. I've just buffed/armoured/armed my pet, I do not want to keep doing it over and over, and I want my pet at max DPS all the time. This is subjective, obviously. But it just isn't fun for me.<br>
<br>
With this point, I'd probably just ignore PC/CP even if it was slightly more efficient. <br>
<br>
However, and here is the kicker:<br>
<br>
4) For most circumstances the evocationalist mage chooses to encounter, PC/CP simply does not cut the mustard. The claims made by Jochan and his cohort are not deliverable.<br>
<br>
What PC/CP *does* allow is for magi to kill 'bigger' things, that cannot be killed using traditional evocation wizzie+pet tactics, even when taken as far as I take them. No evocationalist/sustainer mage is going to solo a WW dragon, that's for sure.<br>
<br>
But is this the objective, to be able to do such a thing? Well, for me, no it is not. The objective is to kill blue cons, preferably the easiest low blue cons, for max xp in minimum time, averaged over solo, duo and single group situations. In this domain, no matter how many words from you sir, I believe the evocationalist sustainer wins. I can output more damage and make a larger contribution to groups from 2 to 6 people than I could if I were a Conjure-based PC/CP mage. Your repeating of the opposite and your condescension toward others with other views does not change the fact.<br>
<br>
Pre-PoP, PC/CP as a tactic for mana regen and for killing mobs, is a joke. When such as I could go into Akheva or Fungus Grove at 60 with 42 AAXP points, and slaughter mobs pretty much nonstop for excellent xp, to my experience faster than any conjure mage with the same gear would be able to manage, I'd have laughed at any mage chaining pets. Sure, they'd use no mana, but they'd waste so much time, coupled with the risk that, sooner or later, they'd mistime it and die, or at least be forced to flee from zone. The fact is, with KEI, SCF, SCM, MC, and lots of FT, a fully buffed/equipped pet and nonstop rains and bolts cut through low blue con mobs like butter, with as close to zero risk as feasibly ever possible.<br>
<br>
Post-PoP, soloing is HARDER, much harder. At first glance, PC looks much better than it did before, for soloing, although in groups almost every mage I know will use the same blast, med and sustain techniques they always did and extremely effectively. But a closer look, at all those wonderful new equippable items to boost the DPS of pets past 80 (and even to 110 in groups), combined with the truly amazing DPS of Firebolt of Tallon, mean that if I can find mobs I can solo at all (a challenge, sadly, and one I would like to see rectified, but that is the subject of another thread), the evocationalist sustain+blast tactics remain solid and very efficient.<br>
<br>
Make ONE pet. Buff, equip and arm it as well as you can. Get buffs from others if you can. Get the most mana regen you can. Sit on your horse and destroy all that comes against you, and make sure that pet stays alive. Then do *NOT* PC, but sit still on your horse, med, let your pet regen (or, better, get a heal for him if available), and repeat.<br>
<br>
In short, in those BoT groups I so love at the moment, I can contribute more to the xp rate of that group than a PC mage can because of my specialization choice and playstyle. You are perfectly allowed to advocate your style, sir, but start rubbishing that of others, and the weaknesses in your argument will be shown too.<br>
<br>
I will deal with just one of your points directly, as it shows a lack of understanding of the evocationalist needs.<br>
<br>
======<br>
Really? I would have thought that even for Evocationists, the efficiency of SCM would have <br>
<br>
been the no-brainer as first choice. ...<br>
======<br>
<br>
I know the effects of SCF and SCM, I don't need to be 'educated'. SCF III gives +7% DPM +7% DPS, whereas SCM III gives +15% DPM zero DPS gain. The reason why SCF III is a no brainer choice for the evocationalist is that **DPS** increase. It is all about killing and killing fast - for low blues, killing fast = more mobs killed for less damage done on the pet and more medding time. Of course, the joy of those 4K+ crits is a factor (fun always is!), but there is also method to this madness. SCM is wonderful yes, but SCF is even better. For me, and for some other magi, at least.<br>
<br>
Open your eyes and accept there are other ways, and they just might be more fun!<br>
<br>
Suzanna. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zacatac>Zacatac</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Sage</span><br>  Posts: 1761<br> <font color=#333333>(2/12/03 7:14:52 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=540.topic&index=29>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Optimal AA path for magicians</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Hmm, how about the &quot;Optimal Path&quot; for the impulse buyer who can't save AA points to save his life?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I'm with Evelle on that one. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
