<br>
Very very true.  In many cases, those buffs are essential for the raid.  I still view it as a bonus, however, rather than the status quo. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=jochangaladar>Jochan Galadar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Sage</span><br>  Posts: 937<br> <font color=#333333>(2/14/03 7:25:53 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=540.topic&index=39>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Optimal AA path for magicians</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I'll remember when a chanter comes ask me for focus items for KEI when I log in tonight, as happens many nights, to say no, as that would be powerlevelling myself (and him!) ROFL. Geez I've heard some nonsense in my time ... LOL<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
My humble apologies Suzanna, for seeming to start a war between magician factions.  I did not say that outside buffing is wrong, but I did say that many take it for granted.  Also, I did say that it should be viewed as a bonus to make things more efficient, rather than the baseline to which you compare effectiveness.<br>
<br>
I also did not try to say that every magician should be reclaim chaining as their standard tactic.  It is amazingly efficient and flexible, but I will not try to bend another magician to that style ( I heartily encourage all to try it out, however.)  In fact, that is not the only style I use, either.  I try to be flexible based on group needs and mob strength.  Whatever is most efficient, with the least amount of outside assistance, is my primary aim.<br>
<br>
One thing I will state is that if you follow my AA path, it will give you a great deal of flexibility and confidence, as efficiency affects all playstyles.  It will allow you to chain pets mana free, resummon pets quickly when needed (such as during possible wipeout, or in raids where the pet falls too early), allow you to gain back mana at a rapid pace, nuke as freely as you dare, and maximize experience rate in both ideal and less-than-ideal grouping settings (from 2-6 people, or even solo, with a huge range of player choices as partners or groupmates.)  In CoTH situations, you will not be dependent on outside infusions of mana to bring the whole raid to the designated area, and there will be minimized delay.<br>
<br>
To me, at least, that is what the &quot;optimal&quot; AA path is all about. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=balanzsonofanz>Balanz son of Anz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Abuser of EZCodes</span><br>  Posts: 2902<br> <font color=#333333>(2/15/03 4:20:28 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=540.topic&index=40>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Optimal AA path for magicians</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Suzanna</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Jochan</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> are both vocal advocates of different approaches to magery.  Respectful conflict between them can be fruitful: I know I have learned much from both of them.  I incorporate elements of both of their approaches in my own style of play.<br>
